						<div class="postbody">I was reading rainwarrior's thread on using start for randomness. ( <!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=2&amp;t=9364">viewtopic.php?f=2&amp;t=9364</a><!-- l --> )<br /><br />I noticed this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">.macro stb&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;val, addr<br />; - store immediate byte using A as temporary register<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; LDA #val<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; STA addr<br />.endmacro<br />; ....<br />&nbsp;stb $0f, $2007<br />&nbsp;stb $12, $2007<br />;...etc..<br /></div><br /><br />I understand this was from a quick example, but seems I like writing macros, maybe see what you think of this syntax:<br /><br />wb, for write byte<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">wb $2007 := #$0f<br /><br />;or<br />PPU_DATA = $2007<br />wb PPU_DATA := #$0f<br />;or<br />lda #$0f<br />ldx #$02<br />wb PPU_DATA := a<br />wb PPU_DATA := x<br />wb PPU_DATA := a<br /><br /></div><br /><br />There is also a decent ww (write word) macro.<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://mynesdev.blogspot.ca/2012/10/assignment-macro.html">http://mynesdev.blogspot.ca/2012/10/ass ... macro.html</a><!-- m --></div>

